          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829619?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 8 月 3 日，前总统唐纳德·特朗普在弗吉尼亚州阿灵顿罗纳德·里根华盛顿国家机场步行接受记者采访。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：亚历克斯·布兰登/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>周四，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>在华盛顿特区的联邦法院表示无罪，全世界的镜头都集中在前总统和现任候选人在被告席上的场面上。该法律案件将在未来几个月内审理，但要记住的政治要点是，这正是民主党希望选民关注的焦点：整天、每一天都在关注特朗普。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>媒体越是关注特朗普的法庭闹剧，公众就越不会关注拜登总统能力的下降或拜登推动家族企业的事实。 （见附近。）起诉书将所有人的注意力集中在特朗普的麻烦上，而不是拜登的记录或有关未来四年的辩论。</p><p>特朗普受审也意味着他的共和党总统提名竞争对手几乎无法引起媒体关注。媒体首先询问他们对特朗普的起诉有何看法，然后如果他们批评得不够充分，就会斥责他们。他们的政策，或者与特朗普先生的分歧，还不如在森林里喊叫。克里斯·克里斯蒂是特朗普最直言不讳的批评者，除了他对特朗普的评价之外，其他人都忽视了他。</p><p>所有这一切都让民主党人欣喜若狂，因为他们希望特朗普成为共和党候选人。他们希望共和党选民通过提名特朗普先生来回应这些指控，作为一种政治报复。不管这本质上意味着共和党将让民主党选择他们的提名人。</p><p>因此，我们在没有明显出口的情况下，倾向于 2024 年的竞选辩论，内容涉及现任总统的年龄和家族企业，以及前总统在 2020 年试图摆脱牢狱之灾时的所作所为。提一个奇怪的想法：这对国家不利。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=D92112D3-1820-448C-AE31-7108C18E7810&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fdonald-trump-democrats-arraignment-2024-election-fd490e8&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">仙境：现在困扰唐纳德·特朗普和亨特·拜登的法律问题的核心是“没有人可以凌驾于法律之上”。瓦格纳集团的叶夫根尼·普里戈任提供了另一种选择：没有规则。图片：美联社/法新社/盖蒂图片社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 22:46:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-democrats-arraignment-2024-election-fd490e8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-democrats-arraignment-2024-election-fd490e8<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>唐纳德·特朗普</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Republicans Return to the SALT Mines]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>八名议员希望补贴民主党州的高税收。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590126124155460614"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590126124155460614"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日下午 6:39 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-republicans-tax-bill-salt-tax-gop-congress-d4b6bc6f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827981?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：安娜·钱梅梅克/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>众议院共和党的微弱多数保证了经常发生的戏剧性事件，最新的一集有一些议员支持民主党的税收政策。来自高税收州的一个团体希望提高州税和地方税的扣除额，他们正在搁置共和党的税收法案来实现这一目标。</p><p>至少八名议员正在采取措施增加可从联邦税单中扣除的州税和地方税金额。如果他们成功了，他们将撤销来之不易的共和党政策。共和党人在 2017 年税制改革中将这一被称为 SALT 的冲销上限限制在 10,000 美元。税收联合委员会估计，这一上限每年使联邦收入增加约 800 亿美元，这有助于抵消企业和个人较低的税率。</p><p>来自高税收州的立法者表示，对于他们的选民来说，这一上限是一项糟糕的协议。 “国会在 SALT 问题上搞砸了纽约人，”该组织领导人之一、众议员尼克·拉洛塔 (Nick LaLota) 7 月表示。 “我不会成为另一次国会试图搞砸纽约的人。”</p><p>与他一起参加的还有纽约州众议员安东尼·德斯波西托、马克·莫利纳罗、迈克·劳勒和安德鲁·加巴里诺，以及新泽西州的汤姆·基恩和克里斯·史密斯，以及加利福尼亚州的迈克·加西亚。据国会山消息人士透露，所有人都表示，他们将投票反对已通过筹款委员会的待决减税方案，除非对其进行修改以增加或取消 SALT 上限。这超过了共和党在预期的党派路线投票中可以承受的失去的五票。</p><p>但缺乏特殊恩惠是如何“搞砸”纽约的呢？州税率由奥尔巴尼等州首府确定，州政客可以自由降低税率。 SALT 扣除可以更容易地保持高税收，因为冲销可以保护居民免受这些惩罚性税率的痛苦。</p><p>由于蓝州税收是对高收入者征收的，因此扣除的好处大部分流向了最富有的纳税人。布鲁金斯学会 2020 年的一项分析发现，收入最高的 1% 的人将从取消 SALT 上限中获得 57% 的收益。</p><p>筹款委员会主席杰森·史密斯（Jason Smith）在 SALT 问题上没有做出让步，并表示他不希望密苏里州选民补贴进步海岸的税收优惠。他在政治上和税收政策优点上都是正确的。取消 SALT 将增加提高联邦税率以弥补收入损失的政治压力。</p><p>即使没有 SALT 行李，筹款计划也很平庸。它确实延长了 2017 年税改法案中即将到期的条款，但也包含了对标准扣除额的误导性提升。仅在两年内，未逐项列出的申报人的一般冲销额将增加 4,000 美元，使联合申报人的总金额达到约 32,000 美元。</p><p>对于收入超过 40 万美元的纳税人来说，奖金会更少，完全减少到 48 万美元左右。与降低所得税税率不同，这种短暂而有限的退税对纳税人增加工作或投资几乎没有什么激励作用。限制收入标准扣除额也是民主党将扩大的一个糟糕的税收先例。</p><p>众议院共和党领导人在与拜登总统达成六月债务上限协议后不久宣布了他们的税收计划，希望这能让选民更多地了解他们的财政优先事项。议长凯文·麦卡锡(Kevin McCarthy)原本寻求在国会8月休会前就该方案进行投票，但SALT僵局已将其最早推迟到9月。</p><p>这场斗争显示了众议院多数派在税收问题上的不团结，而税收问题曾经是共和党的优势。关于特别税收豁免的分歧正中民主党的下怀。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=FB987E80-FC3E-4E48-A9FD-2FE0ACE8A1C8&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fhouse-republicans-tax-bill-salt-tax-gop-congress-d4b6bc6f&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">仙境：共和党总统候选人罗恩·德桑蒂斯、迈克·彭斯、尼基·黑利、蒂姆·斯科特、克里斯·克里斯蒂、维韦克·拉马斯瓦米，甚至唐纳德·特朗普在支出方面都团结一致。所有这些都提供了比其他选择更安全的未来。图片：路透社/祖马出版社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 22:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-republicans-tax-bill-salt-tax-gop-congress-d4b6bc6f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-republicans-tax-bill-salt-tax-gop-congress-d4b6bc6f<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category> Non-metallic Mineral Mining/Quarrying</category><category> Basic Materials/Resources</category><category> Mining/Quarrying</category><category> Salt Extraction</category><category>政府财政</category><category>Government Budget/Taxation</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E Executive News Filter</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> House GOP</category><category>政府财政</category><category>government budget</category><category>税收</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>non-metallic mineral mining</category><category>采石</category><category>basic materials</category><category>资源</category><category>矿业</category><category>salt extraction </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Of Making Many Books There Is No End]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Deciding which ones belong on the Jewish shelf is a sure path to weariness of the flesh. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590093933638186148"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590093933638186148"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Elliot Kaufman</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 3, 2023 6:33 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/of-making-many-books-there-is-no-end-3d8ff0b3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829587?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Kaufman family nonfiction bookcases.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Elliot Kaufman</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> What makes a book Jewish? I am dogged by the question as my wife and I merge our collections. We set aside one bookcase for fiction and two for <em>seforim</em> , the beautifully bound codes of law, volumes of Talmud and selection of commentaries by which a knowledgeable observer could identify precisely what kind of Jews we are. Finally, we devoted two large bookcases to nonfiction, split up between the Jewish and non-Jewish. That is where the trouble set in.</p><p> Blame it on “Vichy France”—the 1972 classic by Robert O. Paxton. The American historian punctured the myth of “passive resistance” to the Nazis erected by Marshal Philippe Pétain, who told Frenchmen in August 1944, “If I could not be your sword, I tried to be your shield.” This excused their behavior even more than his own. Mr. Paxton exposed the regime&#39;s “quest for collaboration,” which “enjoyed mass support and elite participation,” emphasizing “all the things Vichy had done without German pressure and all the things Vichy had begged and implored the Germans to do.”</p><p> When my wife objected to the volume&#39;s placement on our Jewish nonfiction bookcase, I was stunned. Surely, I stammered, the record of Vichy collaboration is of Jewish relevance. But when she gently instructed that we “keep the French away from the Jews,” I couldn&#39;t argue.</p><p> Next came the neoconservatives. I wanted Nathan Glazer&#39;s works of sociology on the Jewish shelf. His 1963 “Beyond the Melting Pot,” with Daniel Patrick Moynihan, has a remarkable second edition from 1970 that apologizes, in so many words, for not seeing the &#39;60s coming. It also includes blunt observations, such as, “Jews have become far more aware of the virtue of conservative working-class and middle-class values, which they always practiced but refused to celebrate,” and quaint ones, such as, “Intermarriage, an important sign of integration, remains low among Jews.”</p><p> The problem, my wife recognized, is that the book also covers the Irish, the Italians and the rest of the New York City mix. Would it really fit next to “Franz Rosenzweig,” by Nahum N. Glatzer, on the Jewish shelves? Suspiciously similar name aside, Glazer was too expansive for our parochial people. I had to restrain myself from arguing that all modern social science is, at bottom, Jewish.</p><p> Defeated twice, and then a third time on the matter of Samuel Goldman&#39;s “Christian Zionism” (me: “it&#39;s <em>Zionism</em> !”; her: “it&#39;s <em>Christian</em> !”), I did the sensible thing: switch sides and carry on the argument.</p><p> Leon Kass&#39;s “The Beginning of Wisdom,” it suddenly occurred to me, had no place on our Jewish bookcase. In this work, beloved to us both, the University of Chicago professor stipulates that he will read the Book of Genesis in “the same spirit in which I read Plato&#39;s Republic”—without “presuppositions and intermediaries,” Jewish or otherwise. Let&#39;s take the man at his word, I taunted. His commentary isn&#39;t Jewish.</p><p> In my wife&#39;s dismay, I saw the danger of the entire enterprise. Who am I to write out from the Jewish tradition such a book, by a Jew turning to a Jewish text for wisdom?</p><p> It is as if I had been misinterpreting the Modern Orthodox Jewish slogan of <em>Torah U&#39;Madda</em> , or Torah and secular learning, to mean nothing deeper than Lenny Bruce&#39;s “Jewish and Goyish” bit, in which the world is divided neatly in two. “ Ray Charles is Jewish. Eddie Cantor is goyish. B&#39;nai Brith</p> is goyish; Hadassah, Jewish,” Bruce joked. “Pumpernickel is Jewish, and, as you know, white bread is very goyish. 。 。 。 All Italians are Jewish. Greeks are goyish—bad sauce.”<p></p><p> The pairings on our Jewish nonfiction bookcase, the product of alphabetical order, are nothing like that. Rather than elevate and denigrate, they jive and commiserate, always honoring the breadth of Jewish experience. Jon Levenson&#39;s “The Love of God: Divine Gift, Human Gratitude, and Mutual Faithfulness in Judaism” is at the ready next to “The Drowned and the Saved” by Primo Levi, for whom Auschwitz was the final word on our Creator. “Fear No Evil,” Soviet refusenik Natan Sharansky&#39;s memoir of his struggle against the KGB to make it to Israel, seems to triumph more fully as it meets Malka Simkovich&#39;s “Discovering Second Temple Literature.”</p><p> The Jewish story bursts out of our crude system of classification. Every book on the Jewish bookcase seems to direct me to another on the non-Jewish one and then to a third, usually by a Jewish author, that could go either way. How about our volume of Kafka&#39;s diaries? As the author of “The Trial” told the assimilated, German-speaking literati at Prague&#39;s Jewish Town Hall in 1912: “Ladies and gentlemen, you know more Yiddish than you think.”</p><p> Some shelves are more Jewish than others, but all are in conversation. Robert Bork&#39;s “Slouching Towards Gomorrah” might sound goyish, and it is on the non-Jewish bookcase, but resting beside Allan Bloom&#39;s “The Closing of the American Mind,” the resonances overwhelm and even wink at the dissonances.</p><p> The profane still must be separated from the sacred, and my wife and I have no desire to place Lori Cox Han&#39;s volume of Pat Buchanan&#39;s White House memos next to</p> Moshe Halbertal&#39;s “Nachmanides.” The two bookcases will stay separate—and separate again, from the fiction and the <em>seforim</em> —but it is my fervent hope that the learning from each of them will mingle and merge in the development of our minds and our marriage.<p></p><p> <em>Mr. Kaufman is the Journal&#39;s letters editor.</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=308CC4D2-8328-495D-966C-0055C8060126&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fof-making-many-books-there-is-no-end-3d8ff0b3&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Journal Editorial Report: The week&#39;s best and worst from Mary O&#39;Grady, Bill McGurn, Allysia Finley and Kim Strassel. Images: Getty Images/The Roanoke Times via AP Composite: Mark Kelly <span class="imageCredit">The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 22:33:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/of-making-many-books-there-is-no-end-3d8ff0b3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/of-making-many-books-there-is-no-end-3d8ff0b3<category> judaism</category><category> seforim</category><category> bookcases</category><category>非小说类</category><category>小说</category><category>家庭</category><category>marriage</category><category> jewish tradition</category><category>纽约市</category><category>france</category><category> nazi germany</category><category> social science</category><category> bible</category><category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Society/Community</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>宗教</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E Executive News Filter</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>religion</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Unprecedented Jack Smith]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> If lying politicians can be prosecuted for &#39;fraud,&#39; as he proposes in the Trump indictment, we&#39;ll need a lot of new prisons. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590128602129743516"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590128602129743516"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/kimberley-a-strassel"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BS063_strass_AM_20180912122055.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/kimberley-a-strassel" itemprop="url" rel="author">Kimberley A. Strassel</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 3, 2023 6:32 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-unprecedented-jack-smith-special-counsel-donald-trump-president-fraud-c076a2ee"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829527?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Special counsel Jack Smith in Washington, Aug. 1.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: saul loeb/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> If there&#39;s one word to describe what everyone might wish Washington would stop producing, it&#39;s “unprecedented.” Yet here we go again, with special counsel Jack Smith&#39;s unprecedented indictment of a politician for engaging in “a conspiracy to defraud the United States.” Be prepared for this new and startlingly elastic precedent to ensnare plenty of others.</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> That&#39;s the biggest problem with Mr. Smith&#39;s latest broadside against <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">Donald Trump</a> , on top of its untested legal theories and evidence of a Justice Department double standard. As former Attorney General William Barr told CNN on Wednesday, “there were reasons not to bring” the case, and among them is “the slippery slope of criminalizing legitimate political activity.”</p><p> Take Mr. Trump out of the equation and consider more broadly what even the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NYT" class="company-name">New York Times</a> calls Mr. Smith&#39;s “novel approach.” A politician can lie to the public, Mr. Smith concedes. Yet if that politician is advised by others that his comments are untruthful and nonetheless uses them to justify acts that undermine government “function,” he is guilty of a conspiracy to defraud the country. Dishonest politicians who act on dubious legal claims? There aren&#39;t enough prisons to hold them all.</p><p> Consider how many politicians might already be doing time had prosecutors applied this standard earlier. Both Al Gore and George W. Bush filed lawsuits in the 2000 election that contained bold if untested legal claims. Surely both candidates had advisers who told them privately that they may have legitimately lost—and neither publicly conceded an inch until the Supreme Court resolved the matter. Might an ultimate sore winner have used this approach to indict the loser for attempting to thwart the democratic process?</p><p> And why limit the theory to election claims? In 2014 the justices held unanimously that President Barack Obama had violated the Constitution by decreeing that the Senate was in recess so that he could install several appointees without confirmation. It was an outrageous move, one that Mr. Obama&#39;s legal counselors certainly warned was a loser, yet the White House vocally insisted the president had total “constitutional authority” to do it. Under Mr. Smith&#39;s standard, that was a <em>lie</em> that Mr. Obama used to <em>defraud</em> the public by jerry-rigging the function of a labor board with illegal appointments.</p><p> What&#39;s the betting someone told President Biden he didn&#39;t have the power to erase $430 billion in student loan debt. Oh, wait! That&#39;s right. He told himself. “I don&#39;t think I have the authority to do it by signing with a pen,” he said in 2021. The House speaker advised him it was illegal: “People think that the president of the United States has the power for debt forgiveness. He does not,” <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/nancy-pelosi">Nancy Pelosi</a> said. Yet Mr. Biden later adopted the <em>lie</em> that he did, and took action to <em>defraud</em> taxpayers by obstructing the federal <em>function</em> of loan processing—until the Supreme Court made him stop. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> Read More Potomac Watch</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunters-sweetheart-plea-deal-justice-department-lawyer-tax-gun-charge-whistleblower-irs-e271d08f?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Hunter&#39;s Sweetheart Plea Deal</a> <span class="date">July 27, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/its-a-shame-about-wray-christopher-fbi-hearing-investigation-agents-washington-d54746d1?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">It&#39;s a Shame About Christopher Wray</a> <span class="date">July 13, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-bidens-smear-strategy-letter-shapley-justice-irs-laptop-whistleblower-7edb0c99?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Hunter Biden&#39;s Smear Strategy</a> <span class="date">July 6, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> If even a former president can be hit with conspiracy charges, what&#39;s to protect a mere congressman, or a failed candidate, or a consultant? For how long did Stacey Abrams falsely dispute her loss in the 2018 Georgia governor&#39;s race and pressure Georgia lawmakers to alter election procedures in ways that might undermine voting integrity on the basis of untruths? Would the advisers who egged her on in that pursuit qualify as co-conspirators, like the lawyers in Mr. Smith&#39;s indictment?</p><p> The press is rooting for the special counsel to go after Republican lawmakers who on the basis of Mr. Trump&#39;s claims objected to slates of electors on Jan. 6, 2021. Let&#39;s line them all up, including dozens of Democrats who objected to slates in 2001, 2005 and 2017—on the basis of <em>lies</em> and with the purpose of conspiring to obstruct (as the Smith indictment puts it) “the lawful federal government function by which the results of the presidential election are collected, counted, and certified.”</p><p> We now know that Rep. Adam Schiff looked at a classified surveillance warrant application against a Trump adviser, <em>lied</em> about its contents publicly, memorialized those lies in an official memo, and used it to help gin up an investigation that definitely impeded the <em>function</em> of the Trump administration. We have evidence that the Federal Bureau of Investigation officials behind that application—James Comey, Andrew McCabe, Peter Strzok—used a dossier full of <em>lies</em> to get that warrant. Fortunately for them, special counsel John Durham</p> chose not to take a flyer by indicting them for conspiracy.<p></p><p> Smith fans will say this is a special case, the “big” lie, a one-time necessity for justice. Yet once a bar is lowered, it will be lowered further. Remember when impeachments, special committees, the stripping of committee assignments, and contempt citations were rare? Of course future prosecutors will take this precedent and expand it in ever more novel ways.</p><p> There are any number of things as certain as death and taxes. One is that politicians will lie, and act on those untruths. Now that might make them felons.</p><p> <em>Write to kim@wsj.com.</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=D92112D3-1820-448C-AE31-7108C18E7810&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-unprecedented-jack-smith-special-counsel-donald-trump-president-fraud-c076a2ee&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">仙境：现在困扰唐纳德·特朗普和亨特·拜登的法律问题的核心是“没有人可以凌驾于法律之上”。瓦格纳集团的叶夫根尼·普里戈任提供了另一种选择：没有规则。 Images: AP/AFP/Getty Images Composite: Mark Kelly <span class="imageCredit">The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 22:32:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-unprecedented-jack-smith-special-counsel-donald-trump-president-fraud-c076a2ee</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-unprecedented-jack-smith-special-counsel-donald-trump-president-fraud-c076a2ee<author><![CDATA[Kimberley A. Strassel]]></author><category> special counsel</category><category> defraud</category><category> doj</category><category>犯罪</category><category>politician</category><category>真相</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>分类</category><category>总统</category><category>选举</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Fraud</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E Executive News Filter</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Unclaimed Funds Brought My Father Back]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> His song royalties reminded me of his Glenn Miller-approved World War II ditty. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10194400307618314568704590014010538071940"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10194400307618314568704590014010538071940"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Michael Joseloff</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 3, 2023 6:31 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/unclaimed-funds-brought-my-father-back-arabella-war-record-label-2f023feb"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829061?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Glenn Miller</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Redferns</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> I got word via email in February that New York state&#39;s unclaimed-funds office was holding money for me, a health-insurance check. I filled out the required paperwork and sent it off. Months went by. Puzzled by the delay, I revisited the funds website and was shocked when my late father&#39;s name, Stanley Joseloff, popped up. He too had unclaimed funds, from song royalties.</p><p> I knew that my father had moonlighted as a songwriter and had written the lyrics to “Dear Arabella,” which Glenn Miller&#39;s orchestra recorded in 1941. Again, I collected and mailed off the necessary paperwork. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="638" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829056?width=639&amp;height=638" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Uncredited</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> This was the second time since dad died in 1989 that Arabella and I had crossed paths. A decade ago, my wife and I were listening to WNYC when Danny Stiles, a broadcaster who billed himself as the “Vicar of Vintage Vinyl,” introduced “The Glenn Miller orchestra playing &#39;Dear Arabella,&#39; with lyrics by Stan Joseloff, music by Sidney Lippman. ” I was thrilled.</p><p> A World War II ditty, “Dear Arabella” tells of a draftee, Pvt. Johnny, who&#39;s writing to his girlfriend back home: “Dear Arabella, this Army life&#39;s OK / But Arabella I miss you more each day / . 。 。 Kindly remember wherever you may be / You&#39;re your private&#39;s private property.”</p><p> After my two Arabella encounters, I searched my father&#39;s old files and discovered more than 50 original songs and poems and a letter to his “Arabella” collaborator. Witty and rhyming, it was classic dad: “I could write a war song of bombs bursting in air, but who&#39;d be left to sing it by the rockets&#39; red glare?”</p><p> My father wanted to make songwriting his career, but his parents weren&#39;t keen on it. So after graduating from college and law school, he took a job as in-house counsel to Lee and JJ Shubert, the powerhouse theater producers and owners, which led to a 12-week gig in 1937 writing songs for “ Billy Rose&#39;s Aquacade.” Rose, an impresario and showman par excellence, staged his extravaganzas in an outdoor amphitheater with a large pool and cast of synchronized swimmers, actors and singers.</p><p> Dad&#39;s big break came when “Dear Arabella” won first prize in a Hearst Newspapers song contest. Glenn Miller chose it as his “Song of the Week,” and Hearst published the music and lyrics in 20 newspapers nationwide.</p><p> Few people outside the family have heard of the song today. But the unclaimed-funds notice and the play on the car radio brought my father back to me in a way nothing else could.</p><p> I&#39;m still waiting for the royalty check, not that I&#39;m going to cash it. I&#39;m going to frame it and place it alongside a treasured 78 rpm record with the trademark dog and phonograph RCA logo and the title “Dear Arabella” on the label.</p><p> <em>Mr. Joseloff is a television producer and author of “Chasing Heisenberg: The Race for the Atom Bomb.”</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=48E03FE9-F0A5-41FB-8532-879C1D176E1F&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Funclaimed-funds-brought-my-father-back-arabella-war-record-label-2f023feb&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> For the first time since 1960, the TV and movie unions representing actors and writers are on strike over issues including better pay on streaming platforms like Netflix, Disney+ and Amazon Prime. Images: Zuma Press/AP/Getty Images/Reuters Composite: Mark Kelly <span class="imageCredit">The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 22:31:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/unclaimed-funds-brought-my-father-back-arabella-war-record-label-2f023feb</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/unclaimed-funds-brought-my-father-back-arabella-war-record-label-2f023feb<category>爸爸</category><category>record</category><category> unclaimed fund</category><category> record label</category><category> arabella</category><category>纽约</category><category>war</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>National/Public Security</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Risk News</category><category> Military Action</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E Executive News Filter</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>public security</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>risk news</category><category> military action</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Talking Cure’ Review: The Joys of Spirited Conversation]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> To chat with those who already agree with us can be comforting, but it proves no substitute for a real, revealing exchange of views. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590116490306890072"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829452?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Johnson, Boswell and company in conversation.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿拉米库存照片</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590116490306890072"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Danny Heitman</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 3, 2023 6:29 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/talking-cure-review-the-joys-of-spirited-conversation-4567781c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> As we&#39;ve often been told, the art of conversation is on life support, ravaged by the excesses of technology. Hooked to our phones and laptops, or so the theory goes, we&#39;ve lost the true gift for gab. Sherry Turkle, one of many writers who have noted the problem, weighed in with her book “Reclaiming Conversation,” in 2015. “We hide from each other even as we&#39;re constantly connected to each other,” Ms. Turkle told readers. “For on our screens, we are tempted to present ourselves as we would like to be.”</p><p> In “Talking Cure,” billed as “an essay on the civilizing power of conversation,” Paula Marantz Cohen echoes some of Ms. Turkle&#39;s laments about online culture as a corrupting influence on conversation. But Ms. Cohen, a professor of English at Drexel University and the dean of its honors college, finds other culprits, too—some well-publicized, and others that readers might not have considered.</p><p> Political polarization quickly rears its head as a conversation killer, blocking the interchange of different perspectives that give a good talk its vitality. “To speak to the converted or the entirely familiar is not to truly converse,” Ms. Cohen writes. “It is to have one&#39;s beliefs reinforced; it is self-soothing but not self-developing.” Mentioning the liberal pedigree of her family, Ms. Cohen writes gratefully about how her world view was expanded by a deep friendship and decades of thoughtful exchanges with a conservative colleague who has since died. “What sustained us in our disagreement,” she recalls, “was our mutual respect, indeed deep affection, for each other. It was a feeling that carried moral as well as emotional weight.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/c3f4f045-936e-457a-a616-697f6cb3f8b8.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Disagreement, Ms. Cohen suggests, is an essential element: “Good conversation digs deep into a subject, turns it over, examines it from angles that might otherwise remain in shadow, and presents hypotheses that may be wrong or even unpleasant, but thought-provoking.” Such openness to opposing viewpoints is now harder to come by in national life. “I used to routinely adopt the devil&#39;s advocate position in class,” she writes, “but I find it harder to do this now, when dissenting viewpoints are less tolerated and when playful or ironic positions are taken literally.”</p><p> As in many of her previous writings, such as “On Human Kindness,” a 2021 book that explored lessons from Shakespeare about empathy, in “Talking Cure” Ms. Cohen looks to literature for useful instruction about her subject. Though she makes numerous arguments for the civic benefits of conversation, the chief value of this book is its abiding reminder of the pleasure of good talk.</p><p> Ms. Cohen is deeply read, and her mind is like a curio cabinet that displays a collection of bright and interesting things.</p><p> In surveying centuries of celebrated talk—touching on figures as varied as Epictetus, William Wordsworth, Virginia Woolf and Langston Hughes—Ms. Cohen&#39;s book offers evidence that for all its challenges, conversation has been an impressively resilient fixture of our species. Her models of good conversation include Samuel Johnson, the 18th-century English wit whose bon mots were copiously recorded by his friend and biographer, James Boswell. But Ms. Cohen makes the point that Boswell was more than a mere stenographer of Johnson&#39;s dinner-table pronouncements. He was a cheerful interlocutor, challenging Johnson&#39;s assumptions in a way that brought out the best in his mentor. It&#39;s a lesson in how conversation can reveal our truest, fullest selves.</p><p> The obstacles to good conversation can be as simple as the spaces in which we&#39;d like to linger and chat. Ms. Cohen sighs at the popular fashion in industrial décor at restaurants, where steel tables and backless chairs don&#39;t exactly invite warm exchanges. More broadly, she finds that talk “of a staged and highly predictable sort” is all around us, “on talk shows, TV panels, interviews, YouTube clips and podcasts,” ersatz conversation that replaces the unpredictable, real thing with an often scripted substitute. One surprising figure she calls out for a negative effect on conversation is Ronald Reagan. His disciplined PR strategy, still a popular model, “flies in the face of the serendipity and spontaneity that characterize real conversation,” she writes. “It may well be that Reagan&#39;s example, through its extraordinary success and superficial appeal, debased political conversation—and beyond that, all conversation—more thoroughly than any other figure in history.”</p><p> One wouldn&#39;t even have to be a particular fan of Reagan to find Ms. Cohen&#39;s assertion a strange piece of hyperbole. (Later in “Talking Cure,” she points to more obvious enemies of conversation, dictators such as Hitler and Stalin.)</p><p> Ms. Cohen&#39;s glancing takedown of the 40th president doesn&#39;t reflect the general tone of “Talking Cure,” which is measured and magnanimous. Elsewhere, she mentions in a more salutary vein Reagan&#39;s convivial chats with his political opponent, House Speaker Tip O&#39;Neill. In a passage arguing that women&#39;s talk has often been unfairly dismissed as trivial, Ms. Cohen sympathetically cites former First Lady Nancy Reagan as a likely victim of sexism.</p><p> Maybe, as with the long-predicted demise of poetry, reading and the republic itself, the art of conversation just might pull through in spite of our folly. The poor state of good talk, after all, is an enduring complaint. Ms. Cohen quotes one commentator&#39;s fear that conversation, “so useful and innocent a pleasure, so fitted for every period and condition of life, and so much in all men&#39;s power, should be so much neglected and abused.”</p><p> That was Jonathan Swift, who left the scene in 1745.</p><p> <em>Mr. Heitman, a columnist for the Baton Rouge Advocate, frequently reviews books for the Journal.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 22:29:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/talking-cure-review-the-joys-of-spirited-conversation-4567781c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/talking-cure-review-the-joys-of-spirited-conversation-4567781c<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item></channel></rss>